44. Capitalis caedis sacta est] i. e. ‘ an atrocious murder was committed.' Caedis is another form of the more common nomi- native caedes‚ as we find aedis for acdes,· torquis for torques, and canis and canes. The epithet capitalis is emphatic, since caedes or caedis would not, taken alone, necessarily imply murder. Young scholars are apt to be embarrassed by the word capitalis. As there is a want of distinctness in some even of our best dictionaries in regard to the modifications of meaning assumed by this word, and their connection with each other, we shall say a few words on the subject.
